    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2
        id="about-tool-heading"
        class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight"
      >
        Understanding Orientation Lock: A Complete Diagnostic Guide
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If you have ever had your phone screen rotate to landscape when you were lying down, you know how crucial the <strong>orientation lock</strong> is. But <strong>what is portrait orientation lock</strong>, and <strong>what does portrait orientation lock do</strong>? Simply put, a <strong>portrait orientation lock</strong> is a built-in operating system feature designed to restrict your mobile display to a vertical layout, preventing automatic screen rotation as you tilt your device. Understanding the <strong>portrait orientation lock meaning</strong> is straightforward: it ensures that your screen remains in portrait mode regardless of physical rotation, which is ideal for reading, texting, and navigating on the move. When you enable this feature, the <strong>screen orientation lockscreen orientation lock</strong> states remain fixed, blocking sensor-driven adjustments so that web apps and interfaces stay in a predictable, upright view.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Finding the Portrait Orientation Lock Button
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Depending on your device, locating the toggle varies. Many users ask: where is the <strong>portrait orientation lock button</strong>? On Apple devices (iOS), the button is located in the Control Center—accessed by swiping down from the top-right corner of the screen. Look for the icon resembling a padlock surrounded by a circular arrow. On Android devices, the equivalent toggle is often named "Auto-rotate" or "Portrait" in the Quick Settings shade. If you cannot find it there, you can configure the <strong>portrait orientation lock in settings</strong> under the "Display" or "Screen" menu. Understanding <strong>what does portrait orientation lock mean</strong> in your system configuration allows you to toggle it on or off dynamically to match your current activity.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Troubleshooting Portrait Orientation Lock Not Working Issues
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Is your screen rotating when it shouldn't, or is your <strong>portrait orientation lock not working</strong>? There are several reasons why this might happen. First, verify that the lock hasn't been disabled accidentally in your control panel. If the padlock icon is highlighted, the lock is active. On some versions of iOS and Android, certain apps override system-level rotation locks (such as video players or mobile games). If you notice the rotation lock behaves inconsistently, check if the issue is app-specific or system-wide. A faulty device accelerometer or gyroscope can also lead to issues where the display fails to respond to movement altogether. In these cases, restarting your device or checking sensor permissions in settings can help restore proper functionality.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Testing Screen Orientation and Web API Compatibility
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        For developers and designers, testing how web applications handle rotation states is critical. While native apps have deep hardware access, web browsers rely on the Screen Orientation API. Unfortunately, modern web browsers do not expose a direct way to detect if a user's system-level <strong>portrait orientation lock</strong> is active. This diagnostic tool bridges that gap using a motion-sensor heuristic. By comparing physical accelerometer changes with browser screen updates, it can infer whether rotation lock is active. Testing these states helps ensure responsive designs render cleanly without clipping or breaking layout boundaries.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        The Practical Applications of Screen Rotation Tests
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Testing your screen rotation behavior is essential for verifying responsive web design and mobile user experience. When building mobile-first websites, designers must account for different aspect ratios and safe area insets. So, <strong>what is orientation lock</strong>? It is the umbrella term for locking screen layouts to prevent layout shift. Safe area insets (such as camera notches and home indicator bars) shift dynamically when the device is rotated. Using an online orientation check tool helps you confirm that your stylesheet responds correctly to every screen angle. It also verifies whether the browser supports programmatic orientation locking via the <code>screen.orientation.lock()</code> API, which is highly useful for progressive web applications (PWAs) that require a specific layout direction.
      </p>
    </article>

    <!-- Visible FAQ matching FAQ JSON-LD -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 max-w-4xl mx-auto w-full mt-6">
