  <!-- How it works Modal -->
  <div
    id="how-it-works-modal"
    class="fixed inset-0 bg-primary/20 backdrop-blur-sm z-50 flex items-center justify-center p-4 transition-all duration-300 hidden"
  >
    <div
      class="bg-canvas rounded-2xl max-w-lg w-full p-6 border border-hairline shadow-modal flex flex-col gap-4 animate-scale-in max-h-[85vh] overflow-y-auto"
    >
      <div
        class="flex justify-between items-center pb-2 border-b border-hairline-soft"
      >
        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary">
          Orientation Lock Guide
        </h3>
        <button
          type="button"
          id="close-modal-btn"
          class="text-stone hover:text-primary transition-all text-lg cursor-pointer"
        >
          ✕
        </button>
      </div>

      <div class="text-xs text-slate leading-relaxed flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          1. Checking Screen Orientation API
        </h4>
        <p>
          We read <code>window.screen.orientation</code> directly to output the current layout state (Portrait vs Landscape, primary vs secondary) 
          and rotation angles (0°, 90°, 180°, 270°). The central phone silhouette updates dynamically to match.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Best-Effort Lock Heuristic</h4>
        <p>
          OS-level orientation lock status is hidden from standard web scripting. This tool infers the status by analyzing 
          physical accelerometer movement. If you rotate your device but the screen fails to align, the system detects this 
          and flags rotation lock as active.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. Guided Rotation Checklist</h4>
        <p>
          Rotate your device in all four directions to verify that every orientation transition functions. On some mobile 
          operating systems (like Apple iOS), Portrait-Secondary (upside down) is disabled at the system level for phone layouts.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">4. Viewport & Safe-Area Bounds</h4>
        <p>
          Displays the layout properties including the pixel ratios and active safe area bounds (e.g. notch regions), which 
          helps web designers review CSS responsive viewport boundaries.
        </p>
